[7] Australia (Victoria)
Date: Mon 26 Aug 2013
Source: The Age [abridged & edited]
http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/measles-outbreak-fear-as-virus-spreads-20=130826-2skyo.html


Health authorities are fearing a measles outbreak in Victoria after 10 cases of the potentially fatal virus [infection] were diagnosed in Melbourne over the past 3 weeks. Victoria's Chief Health Officer Rosemary Lester said 2 separate clusters of the highly contagious disease had now been identified and that people in the northern and eastern suburbs of Melbourne may be at risk.

Dr Lester said the 1st cluster involved a 26-year-old East Brunswick man who passed the disease on to 4 people. This man flew on a domestic flight between Brisbane and Melbourne on 31 Jul 2013 and spent time whilst infectious at Northland shopping centre, including the cinemas http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/measles-detected-sparking-outbreak-fears-20130808-2ri3a.html?rand=3D1377480147345, on 1 Aug 2013. The man also attended an East Brunswick medical practice on 3 Aug 2013.

The 2nd cluster is linked to a 21-year-old man who recently flew home to Australia from Europe. He has passed the illness on to 3 family members and was infectious from 1-10 Aug 2013. During this time, he or his family were in contact with people in suburbs including Ivanhoe, Collingwood, Upper Heidelberg and Donvale. People susceptible to the virus may have also been exposed to infected people in Reservoir, Coburg, Preston, Parkville, Brunswick and Box Hill.

Dr Lester said she was also concerned about patients who attended Box Hill Hospital emergency department on 15 Aug 2013 because a Chinese woman who presented to the hospital that day has since been diagnosed with measles. "We are not aware of any other cases at this stage from the woman at Box Hill Hospital, but people are asked to be alert for symptoms. She also attended 2 medical centres, which are alerting medical staff and patients," Dr Lester said.

Because the virus has an average incubation period of 10 days before symptoms present, Dr Lester said further cases may emerge. She said the illness usually begins with common cold symptoms such as fever, sore throat, red eyes and a cough. The characteristic measles rash usually begins 3-7 days after the 1st symptoms, generally starting on the face and then spreading to the rest of the body. "Anyone developing these symptoms is advised to ring ahead to their GP or hospital and alert them that they have fever and a rash," Dr Lester said.

Measles, which is also known as rubeola, is a very contagious virus. Estimates suggest one person will infect about 9 in every 10 people who have not had the illness or are unvaccinated. Serious and sometimes fatal complications include pneumonia and encephalitis. The Victorian clusters come after an alarming surge of measles in the UK this year [2013] prompted an urgent vaccination campaign. British health authorities believe the outbreak was caused by a lack of herd immunity among young people who were not vaccinated in the early 2000s.

--
Communicated by:
Julia Medew
http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/by/Julia-Medew

[This report is of another occurrence of spread of infection associated with air travel by unvaccinated individuals, both within one country and, this time, on the other side of the world, whereby a vaccinated traveller from an endemic area has initiated one case via intercontinental air travel and the other by internal air travel. - Mod.CP

